A Modern Approach to SoC Verification — From Virtual Models to Emulation, presented by Karthik Padmakumar (Arm) & Luis E. Rodriguez (Siemens EDA)

The discussion covers the modern approach to SoC verification in two parts: the what and why, and then the how. Chiplets are revolutionizing system design and have become the new building blocks of computing. AI should be looked at as a full stack: not just hardware, but firmware and software together, which requires an aggressive shift left to stay competitive as the AI industry moves quickly and things become obsolete fast. Three components are needed: a pre-verified compute subsystem, software optimization on that subsystem, and co-validation of software and hardware. This sits under open standards of FCSA (foundation chiplet system architecture) released to OCP and interoperability guidelines. The chiplet work includes the ARM Neoverse compute subsystem announced at OCP in August 2023, positioned as a fast path to production silicon with strong partner results on resources and time to market.

The full stack also means compressing time-to-market. The flow goes from IP through virtual prototyping for software development, then system integration and some shift left for software acceleration—but more is needed. That is where ARM CSS and ecosystem collaboration come in, including the ATD ecosystem where silicon vendors and EDA vendors work with Arm to integrate IPs and flows and accelerate the development timeline with co-validation and software development in parallel. The modern shift-left approach combines optimized CSS with that ecosystem play.

Luis Rodriguez describes Siemens' collaboration with Arm. ASIC first-time silicon success has been declining while projects run late; CSS aims to address this. Shift-left has succeeded in areas like SSDs for NVMe (firmware-critical) and CXL, and is being brought to the Arm ecosystem through ATD. Building blocks start from standards-based verification IP: AMBA, AXI, low power, PCI Express, CXL models as SystemVerilog-class VIPs, configurable for fault injection and randomized behavior. These VIPs are used at IP level and are brought to system level at CSS through SystemC and TLM, with a shim to ARM FAST models so CSS blocks (CMN, I/O, etc.) can be simulated with RTL, FAST model, and VIP. InfraBoard FVP can connect through TLM to AXI VIPs; PCI Express subsystems can be pre-validated PSA-compliant. Teams can load UEFI images, boot, run test cases like SBSA, and let firmware teams validate while hardware substitutes VIP for IP blocks in a modular bring-up. Multiple chiplets can be modeled via PCI Express or UCIE. Shift left lets firmware start earlier, enables hardware-firmware co-debug in RTL (waveforms, step-through, breakpoints in firmware with RTL paused), and runs faster than some expect—on the order of hundreds of millions of instructions to UEFI in under two hours in their setup, with tarmac trace and flit-level VIP tracker output.

A call to action asks for contributions to the shift-left flow, contribution to the BSA/SBSA pre-silicon compliance program, and contribution to the FCSA spec provided to OCP. Open standards (PCIe, CXL, UCIe, etc.), QEMU, and open UEFI debugging are all part of the methodology. Partnerships are open through ATD or direct outreach.
